An organic anion that is the conjugate base of tetracycline obtained by deprotonation of the two enolic hydroxy groups and protonation of the tertiary amino group.
An organophosphate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the triphosphate OH groups of adenosine thiamine triphosphate.
An adenosine 5'-phosphate obtained by formal condensation of the hydroxy group of thiamine with the triphosphate group of ATP.
An organophosphate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate OH groups of 2-oxo-AMP.
A purine ribonucleoside 5'-monophosphate that is the 2-oxo derivative of AMP.
A purine 2'-deoxyribonucleoside 5'-diphosphate that is the 8-oxo derivative of dADP.
A linear amino trisaccharide comprising a sequence of N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosamine, beta-D-galactose and another N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosamine connected by (1->4) linkages.
A lipid A oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the phosphate and carboxy groups and protonation of the free amino groups of (beta-L-Ara4N)2-(KDO)2-lipid A; major species at pH 7.3.
A monocarboxylic acid anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy and one of the phosphonate OH groups of 3-phosphonopyruvic acid.
A purine 2'-deoxyribonucleoside 5'-diphosphate that is the 8-oxo derivative of dADP.
A linear amino trisaccharide consisting of three N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosamine residues linked (1->4).

A glycopeptidolipid consisting of L-lysine, to the N-2 of which is attached an N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosaminyl-(1->4)-N-acetylmuramoyl moiety connected to the amino terminus of the dipeptide L-alanyl-D-isoglutamine, and to the N-6 of which is attached a stearoyl group.
An organic cation that is the conjugate acid of (R)-adrenaline, obtained by protonation of the amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
A 3-oxo-fatty acyl-CoA(4-) arising from deprotonation of the phosphate and diphosphate groups of 3-oxooctadecanoyl-CoA; major species at pH 7.3.
A 3-hydroxy fatty acyl-CoA(4-) arising from deprotonation of the phosphate and diphosphate groups of 3-hydroxyoctadecanoyl-CoA; major species at pH 7.3.
A lipid A derivative comprising lipid A glycosylated with two 3-deoxy-D-manno-octulosonic acid (KDO) residues and carrying two additional 4-amino-4-deoxy-beta-L-arabinopyranosyl esterifying groups.
A 3-oxo-fatty acyl-CoA(4-) arising from deprotonation of the phosphate and diphosphate groups of 7-methyl-3-oxooct-6-enoyl-CoA; major species at pH 7.3.
beta-D-GlcpNAc-(1->6)-D-GalpNAc in which the anomeric configuration of the reducing-end GalNAc residue is alpha.
A 2,3-trans-enoyl CoA(4-) arising from deprotonation of the phosphate and diphosphate groups of trans-2-octadecenoyl-CoA; major species at pH 7.3.

A linear amino trisaccharide consisting of an N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosamine residue linked (1->6) to a beta-D-galactose residue which is itself linked (1->4) to another N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosamine residue at the reducing end.
An imidazolidine-2,4-dione that is hydantoin substituted at position 1 by a [(5-nitro-2-furyl)methylene]amino group. An antibiotic that damages bacterial DNA.

A diaminopyridine that is 2,6-diaminopyridine substituted at position 3 by a phenylazo group. A local anesthetic that has topical analgesic effect on mucosa lining of the urinary tract. Its use is limited by problems with toxicity (primarily blood disorders) and potential carcinogenicity.

A benzamide obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of 4-[(2-methylhydrazino)methyl]benzoic acid with the amino group of isopropylamine. An antineoplastic chemotherapy drug used for treatment of Hodgkin's lymphoma. Metabolism yields azo-procarbazine and hydrogen peroxide, which results in the breaking of DNA strands.
A synthetic glucocorticoid that is the 16,17-acetonide of triamcinolone. Used to treat various skin infections.

A hydrochloride obtained by combining phenazopyridine with one equivalent of hydrochloric acid. A local anesthetic that has topical analgesic effect on mucosa lining of the urinary tract. Its use is limited by problems with toxicity (primarily blood disorders) and potential carcinogenicity.
An organic cation that is the conjugate acid of phenazopyridine.
A glucotriose consisting of two alpha-D-glucose residues and a beta-D-glucose at the reducing end in a linear sequence and joined by (1->6) linkages.
A glycosylglucose in which two beta-D-glucose residues are linked (1->6).
An amino disaccharide consisting of N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosamine, substituted on O-3 with a 1-carboxyethyl group and linked (1->4) to a second N-acetyl-beta-D-glucosamine residue.
An acyl-CoA(4-) arising from deprotonation of the phosphate and diphosphate functions of isopalmitoyl-CoA. Major species at pH 7.3.
A 3-oxo-fatty acyl-CoA(4-) arising from deprotonation of the phosphate and diphosphate functions of 3-oxoisooctadecanoyl-CoA.
An acyl-CoA(4-) arising from deprotonation of the phosphate and diphosphate functions of isotridecanoyl-CoA.

A hydrochloride obtained by combining procarbazine with one equivalent of hydrochloric acid. An antineoplastic chemotherapy drug used for treatment of Hodgkin's lymphoma. Metabolism yields azo-procarbazine and hydrogen peroxide, which results in the breaking of DNA strands.
A ketoaldonic acid obtained formally by deamination of neuraminic acid. Although not containing nitrogen it is regarded as being a member of the sialic acid family.
